rules.fullText:
{{BOLD}}<GG15>{{/BOLD}} {{BOLD}}Offensive Robots get the “benefit of the doubt” when judgement calls are required.{{/BOLD}} In a case where a {{LINK:#headreferee}}Head Referee{{/LINK}} is forced to make a judgment call regarding a destructive interaction between a {{LINK:#defensive}}Defensive{{/LINK}} and {{LINK:#offensive}}Offensive{{/LINK}} {{LINK:#robot}}Robot{{/LINK}}, or an interaction which results in a questionable {{LINK:#violation}}Violation{{/LINK}}, referees will decide in favor of the {{LINK:#offensive}}Offensive{{/LINK}} {{LINK:#robot}}Robot{{/LINK}}. This also applies during the {{LINK:#autonomousperiod}}Autonomous Period{{/LINK}} (see SG7a).

{{CALLOUT}} {{LINK:#headreferee}}Head Referees{{/LINK}} must apply judgment when determining whether each {{LINK:#robot}}Robot{{/LINK}} in a <GG15> interaction was {{LINK:#defensive}}Defensive{{/LINK}} or {{LINK:#offensive}}Offensive{{/LINK}}, and in some cases may need to consider which {{LINK:#robot}}Robot{{/LINK}} was more {{LINK:#defensive}}Defensive{{/LINK}} or {{LINK:#offensive}}Offensive{{/LINK}} than another within the larger context of the {{LINK:#match}}Match{{/LINK}}. In these cases, the {{LINK:#headreferee}}Head Referee{{/LINK}} should decide in favor of the less {{LINK:#defensive}}Defensive{{/LINK}} and/or more {{LINK:#offensive}}Offensive{{/LINK}} {{LINK:#robot}}Robot{{/LINK}} based on the definitions and guidance in this game manual.
 {{/CALLOUT}}

